      <div class="tip-box"><strong>Travel note:</strong> To enter France or any EU country, rabies vaccination is compulsory. Allow 21 days between primary rabies vaccination and crossing the border.</div>

      <h2>Deworming & parasite control</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Deworming (internal parasites):</strong> Every 3 months until 6 months of age, then twice yearly for life. In the Valais mountains, more frequent treatment is recommended (dogs in contact with wildlife)</li>
        <li><strong>Ticks:</strong> Prevention from March to November in Switzerland. Spot-on or collar (Seresto). Manual check after every woodland walk</li>
        <li><strong>Fleas:</strong> Monthly spot-on or quarterly treatment depending on product. If infestation occurs, treat the environment too (home, car)</li>
        <li><strong>Mosquitoes / heartworm:</strong> Relevant if you travel with your dog to southern France, Spain, or Italy — ask your vet before departure</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Breed-specific conditions</h2>
      <h3>Pomsky</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Patellar luxation (genetically monitored in our breeding dogs)</li>
        <li>Hip dysplasia (rare in small individuals, more common in heavier F1s)</li>
        <li>Hereditary eye conditions (annual testing on all our adults)</li>
        <li>Alopecia X (hormonal coat loss — cosmetic, not painful)</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Pomeranian</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Patellar luxation (most common condition in small breeds)</li>
        <li>Tracheal collapse (never use a collar — harness only, always)</li>
        <li>Hypoglycaemia in very young puppies (watch closely from 8 to 14 weeks)</li>
        <li>Dental problems (small jaw — annual scale and polish from 2 years)</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Siberian Husky</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Hereditary cataracts (annual CAER test on all our adults)</li>
        <li>Progressive retinal atrophy (genetic test included)</li>
        <li>Hip dysplasia (rare but possible in large-framed individuals)</li>
        <li>Skin sensitivity (avoid harsh shampoos)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Warning signs — see a vet immediately</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Repeated vomiting over 24 hours, or blood in vomit</li>
        <li>Persistent bloody diarrhoea</li>
        <li>Sudden marked lethargy, total food refusal lasting more than 48 hours</li>
        <li>Distended, hard abdomen (absolute emergency: gastric torsion)</li>
        <li>Chronic cough or laboured breathing</li>
        <li>Lameness that does not resolve within 24 hours</li>
        <li>Red eyes or heavy eye discharge</li>
        <li>Seizures — immediate emergency vet visit</li>
      </ul>
